@endnode

@node "Introduction" "SLIPCall Users Guide"

@{b} Introduction
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

  This manual is a description of SLIPCall, a dialer for AmiTCP.

  To use SLIPCall you will need an installed AmiTCP version 3.0b or later.

  SLIPCall requires Holger Kruse's ppp.device version 1.30 or later to be
  able to make a PPP connection. (Can be found on Aminet)

  SLIPCall requires Workbench 2.0 or higher to run. It uses many 2.04
  features and has been designed to be as user-friendly possible.

  SLIPCall requires `bgui.library' version 40.3 or higher to run. This
  library is (C) Jan van den Baard and is included in the distribution
  archive.



@endnode

@node "Features" "SLIPCall Users Guide"

@{b} Features
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 * Includes both MWB and NI Icons.
 * Requires Kickstart 2.04 or higher.
 * It's a commodity.
 * Nice GUI.
 * Supports new 3.0 features (newlook menus...)
 * Style Guide compliant.
 * Completely font-sensitive.
 * Keyboard short-cuts for most menus and gadgets.
 * Almost all settings can be easily changed from within SLIPCall.
 * Easy to configure.
 * ARexx interface.
 * Encrypted and hidden password in settings and configuration file.
 * Fast login procedure.
 * Poll function.
 * Support for both static and dynamic IP addresses.
 * Support for both static and dynamic gateways.
 * Supports more than one nameserver.
 * Able to resume a lost connection.
 * Supports SLIP, CSLIP and PPP.
 * Detailed log file.
 * Phonebill scanner included.


 @{b}Supported Providers@{ub}

 * CanIt AB
 * Algonet AB
 * ABC Klubben
 * Oden Telecom
 * Kuai Connection
 * University of Uppsala



@endnode

@node "Installation" "SLIPCall Users Guide"

@{b} Installation
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

  Use the appropriate installation icon in the `Install' drawer.
  Installation uses Commodore's installer utility and should be a
  doddle.

  If you will be running PPP, you must install Holger Kruse's ppp.device
  version 1.30 or later. You don't have to follow his instructions though,
  just copy the ppp.device to DEVS:Networks/ppp.device. SLIPCall handles
  the rest.

  SLIPCall normally requires `PROGDIR:config' directory to save it's
  configuration files in. If this directory doesn't exist, SLIPCall is
  unable to read and save it's default configuration file.

  If you wish SLIPCall to use another configuration file than it's default,
  you can use the `CONFIG' command line switch (from the Shell) or the
  `CONFIG' tooltype from the Workbench.

  When you start SLIPCall for the first time you should set your
  preferences before using it further.



@endnode

@node "Usage" "SLIPCall Users Guide"

@{b} Usage
 ŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 From Workbench:

    Just click the icon twice, as usual.

 From Shell:

    Just enter SLIPCall and press enter.




 There's some command line arguments/ToolTypes you can set, though:


    @{b}CX_PRIORITY@{ub} (-127 - 128, default is 0)

        Commodity priority

    @{b}CX_POPUP@{ub}    (YES or NO, default is YES)

        Open window at startup?

    @{b}CX_POPKEY@{ub}   (any keycombination, default is ctrl alt s)

        Commodity hotkey

    @{b}ACTION@{ub}      (DIAL, RESUME, POLL, CHECK or NONE, default is NONE)

        What do you want me to do right after startup?

        DIAL will try to establish a connection, and wait for you
             to hangup.

        RESUME will try to resume a lost connection

        POLL will try to establish a connection, execute your mail
             commands, hangup and quit.

        CHECK will just try to open your serial device, close it and
              quit. For script usage. When using this option, the mainwindow
              will not open, and the requesters are disabled. The information
              is written to the logfile though.

    @{b}WINDOW@{ub}      (YES or NO, default is NO)

        Opens a simple window, showing modem output.

    @{b}REQUESTER@{ub}   (YES or NO, default is YES)

        If set to NO, the message requesters won't show up.

    @{b}CONFIG@{ub}     (Any filename, default is PROGDIR:config/SLIPCall.config)

        Use custom settings file.

    @{b}TERMLOG@{ub}    (Any filename, default is none)

        Output file all data read by the modem. Will be saved even if the
        terminal window isn't open.



@endnode

