@node "Settings Misc" "SLIPCall Users Guide"

@{b} Settings Miscellaneous
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}
 (default value)


 @{b}Log file:@{ub}

    The full path to your logfile. (PROGDIR:SLIPCall.log)

 @{b}AmiTCP user:@{ub}

    Your username specified in AmiTCP:db/passwd. (none)

 @{b}Retries:@{ub}

    Number of retries SLIPCall does to establish a connection. (10)

 @{b}Timeout:@{ub}

    Seconds SLIPCall should wait before timeout when waiting for a string.
    While dialing, this is the timeout before getting CONNECT. Otherwise
    it is the timeout when waiting for a string to arrive to the serial
    port. (60)

 @{b}Delay:@{ub}

    Seconds SLIPCall should wait between dial retries. (0)

 @{b}Clock:@{ub}

    Show the Online clock? (Yes)



@endnode

@node "Settings Mail" "SLIPCall Users Guide"

@{b} Settings Mail
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}
 (default value)


 @{b}Get mail:@{ub}

    Command to get mail from your mailserver. AmiPOP is an example. Any
    valid commandline is allowed. Command will be executed right after
    a successfull login, and only if the checkbox is checked. (none)

 @{b}Get news:@{ub}

    Command to get news from your newsserver. NNTPGet is an example.
    Any valid commandline is allowed. Command will be executed right after
    a successfull login, and only if the checkbox is checked. (none)

 @{b}Send mail/news:@{ub}

    Command to send mail and news to your mail/newsserver. A script is
    the most efficient here. an example. Any valid commandline is allowed.
    Command will be executed right after a successfull login, and only if
    the checkbox is checked. (none)



@endnode

@node "Settings Provider" "SLIPCall Users Guide"

@{b} Settings Provider
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}
 (default value)


 @{b}Provider:@{ub}

    The name of your provider. (none)

 @{b}Phone:@{ub}

    The phonenumber to your providers modem pool. (none)

 @{b}Password:@{ub}

    The password you have on your account. This will be hidden and
    encrypted as soon as you press enter or tab.

 @{b}Domain:@{ub}

    Your providers domain, for example `canit.se' (none)

 @{b}HostIP:@{ub}

    The IP address of your host. (i.e. the machine you are calling)
    Set to 0.0.0.0 if it's dynamically assigned at login, or you are
    running PPP. (0.0.0.0)

 @{b}Nameserver:@{ub}

    The nameserver you want to use, addressed by IP address.
    More than one address can be specified by separating them with
    a '|'. The addresses will be searched in entered order. Up to 16 full
    addresses is supported. (0.0.0.0)

 @{b}Gateway:@{ub}

    The gateway IP you should use. Ask your provider.
    Set to 0.0.0.0 if it's dynamically assigned at login or you are
    running PPP. (0.0.0.0)

 @{b}Static IP:@{ub}

    Your IP address if you have a static account. Set to 0.0.0.0 if you
    have a dynamic account. (0.0.0.0)

 @{b}MTU:@{ub}

    Max Transfer Unit. Ask your provider what this should be set to.
    1500 mostly is a good value. (1500)

 @{b}Protocol:@{ub}

    The protocol you want to use. SLIP, CSLIP or PPP. (CSLIP)



@endnode

@node "Settings Serial" "SLIPCall Users Guide"

@{b} Settings Serial
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}
 (default value)


 @{b}Device:@{ub}

    Serial device to use. (serial.device)

 @{b}Unit:@{ub}

    The unit of the serial device to use. (0)

 @{b}Speed:@{ub}

    The data speed between the computer and modem in bps. (38400)

 @{b}Handshake:@{ub}

    Handshaking method. XON/XOFF or RTS/CTS. (RTS/CTS)

 @{b}Databits:@{ub}

    The number of databits to use. (8)

 @{b}Parity:@{ub}

    The parity to use. (None)

 @{b}Stopbits:@{ub}

    The number of stopbits to use. (1)



@endnode

@node "Settings Modem" "SLIPCall Users Guide"

@{b} Settings Modem
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}
 (default value)


 In these strings, following control characters are allowed:

     ~  Delay 0.5 seconds.
     \r Send a carriage return. (backslash & r)
     \n Send a linefeed.        (backslash & n)
     \\ Send a backslash.       (backslash & backslash)

 When a \r (CR) is sent, and it isn't the last character in the string,
 SLIPCall will wait for an OK from the modem before it continues with the
 string.

 SLIPCall does NOT append a CR at the End of the strings by itself!


 @{b}Init string:@{ub}

    The command(s) sent to the modem before dial up.
    (AT&F0&D0\r)

 @{b}Dial prefix:@{ub}

    The command(s) preceeding the phonenumber.
    (ATDT)

 @{b}Dial suffix:@{ub}

    The command(s) following the phonenumber.
    (\r)

 @{b}Hangup string:@{ub}

    The string sent to the modem when hanging up.
    (+++~~~~ATH0\r)

 @{b}Reset string:@{ub}

    The command(s) sent to the modem after hangup.
    (ATZ\r)




@endnode

@node "Settings Script" "SLIPCall Users Guide"

@{b} Settings Script
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}
 (default value)

 The script is divided into 3 subpages; line 1-4, line 5-8 and line 9-12.


 @{b}Popup menu:@{ub}

    Action. Available choices are

        Wait for        - Waits for following string. case sensitive.
        Send            - Sends following string. case sensitive.
        Send Password   - Sends your password.
        Scan IP         - Waits for following string, and try to extract
                          an IP address received after the string.
        Scan Gateway    - Waits for following string, and try to extract
                          a gateway IP received after the string.
        None            - Does nothing

 @{b}String:@{ub}

    The string you should send or wait for.

     In these strings, following control characters are allowed:

        \r Send a carriage return. (backslash & r)
        \n Send a linefeed.        (backslash & n)
        \\ Send a backslash.       (backslash & backslash)




 No CR is appended to the strings you send, except when you are using the
 'Send Password' action. You have to do this yourself, by adding a \\r at the
 End of the string you are sending.

Example:

 Login procedure as follows

 ---8<---

 uno login: egge
 Password: <my password, hidden>

 Last logon from: dslip19.canit.se

 You have new mail!
 /home/2/egge# slip
 Starting auto slip for egge
 Slip server is 193.13.228.1
 You are 193.13.228.120

 ---8<---


 Provider->Host IP   = 0.0.0.0
 Provider->Gateway   = 0.0.0.0
 Provider->Static IP = 0.0.0.0


 Script as follows

 ---8<---

 Wait for       ogin:
 Send           egge\r
 Wait for       assword:
 Send Password
 Wait for       egge#
 Send           slip\r
 Scan Gateway   Slip server is
 Scan IP        You are
 None
 None
 None
 None

 ---8<---




@endnode

@node "ARexx" "SLIPCall Users Guide"

@{b} ARexx Interface
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

 SLIPCall features a nice ARexx interface, letting you use it in complex
 scripts, or simular.

 When executing an ARexx command, the REQUESTER keyword is always set to
 NO until command returns.

 The portname always is 'RXSLIP.1'.

 The ARexx commands SLIPCall understands are following:

 @{b}DIAL@{ub}

    Act as you clicked the Dial button.

    Returns 0 if successful, 5 if already connected and 10 if the dialup
    fails for any reason.

 @{b}RESUME@{ub}

    Act as you clicked the Resume button.

    Returns 0 if successful, 5 if already connected and 10 if the resume
    fails for any reason.

 @{b}HANGUP@{ub}

    Act as you clicked the Hang up button.

    Always returns 0.

 @{b}POPUP@{ub}

    Opens the hidden window. Acts as you pressed the commodity hotkey.

    Always returns 0.

 @{b}HIDE@{ub}

    Hides the window. Acts as you clicked the Hide button.

    Returns 0 if successful and 10 if the settings window is open.

 @{b}QUIT FORCE/S@{ub}

    Quit SLIPCall. If you're connected, a requester will pop up and ask you
    to confirm, unless you specified the FORCE switch.

    Returns 0 if successful and 10 if the user canceled when confirming.

 @{b}LOAD CONFIG/K/A@{ub}

    Loads a settings file. The CONFIG keyword is required, and you must
    specify the absolute path to the file.

    Ex: LOAD CONFIG PROGDIR:config/SLIPCall.config

    Returns 0 if successful, and 5 if connected.

 @{b}CHECK@{ub}

    Tries to open the serial device. If successful, the device is immediately
    closed again. The result is saved to the logfile.

    Returns 0 if successful, 20 otherwise.







@endnode

@node "Troubleshooting" "SLIPCall Users Guide"

@{b} Troubleshooting
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ@{ub}

@{b}    * I'm having problem with the modem initializing or dialing.
      Nothing happens!@{ub}

      1) Do you have a carriage return (\r (backslash & r)) after the
         init string, and in the Dial suffix string?
      2) Do you have the ATD command in your Dial prefix string?

@{b}    * My modem disconnects just before AmiTCP is started.@{ub}

      Do you have the DTR check on the modem disabled? (AT&D0)
      If not, do it in your modem init or dial prefix.

@{b}    * SLIPCall won't login as it should, and yes, my script seems ok!@{ub}

      1) Do you have a carriage return (\r (backslash & r)) at the End of the
         strings you are sending in the script?
      2) Did you check your modem init? Maybe the defult AT&F0 won't work with
         your modem.

@{b}    * SLIPCall established a connection, but I can't contact any
      machine on the net.@{ub}

      Check your serial preferences in Workbench. You should set it
      to RTS/CTS, 8 databits, No parity and 1 stopbit.

@{b}    * I'm having problem when using PPP.@{ub}

      1) Do you have ppp.device in DEVS:Networks/ ?
      2) Check the file 'AmiTCP:db/interfaces' to see if it contains the
         line 'ppp0 DEV=DEVS:Networks/ppp.device UNIT=0 IPTYPE=33 NOARP P2P'

@{b}    * SLIPCall doesn't hangup when it should.@{ub}

      1) Check your Hangup string. Maybe you have to add some delay between the
         '+++' and your hangup command.

      2) Make sure you haven't disabled the escape sequence on the modem.
         (i.e. the +++ characters, Register S2)

         If you have, you should add 'S2=43' to your initstring in SLIPCall.



@endnode

